The text describes a completion pathway for graduates of an advanced (three-year) diploma program in Building Renovation Technology at an Ontario college, who wish to pursue a degree in Construction Management. The degree is a Honours Bachelor of Technology (Construction Management) which is a four-year program. It combines theory, applied research, field study, and hands-on practical education with a focus on both technical and managerial skills.

The program is fully accredited by the Canadian Institute of Quantity Surveyors (CIQS) and graduates are eligible to obtain Gold Seal Certification (GSC) offered by the Canadian Construction Association (CCA). The program includes a mandatory field experience semester in the spring/summer of the third year. Students must complete a minimum of 450 hours of field experience or equivalent past experience in construction management. They can fulfill this requirement through a Field Experience course (TCOP 1001) or Prior Learning Assessment Recognition (PLAR).

Year 3 and Year 4 are required for the Bachelor's degree in Construction Management. The academic credential designation is Hons. B.Tech (Construction Management).

The Honours Bachelor of Technology (Construction Management) program at the college prepares students for careers in various roles within the construction industry, including but not limited to: construction manager, project manager, project coordinator, field engineer, site superintendent, estimator, project monitor, building science specialist, building condition assessor, construction sales manager, construction claims specialist, construction quality control specialist, construction health and safety specialist, construction cost consultant, developer, project controls specialist, site inspector, contractor, and subcontractor.

The program is fully accredited by the Canadian Institute of Quantity Surveyors (CIQS), the Chartered Institute of Building (CIOB), and the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors (RICS). Graduates are qualified to obtain professional memberships in various construction management associations, including the Canadian Institute of Quantity Surveyors (CIQS), which grants Professional Quantity Surveyors (PQS) or Construction Estimator Certified (CEC) designations. The academic requirements for these professional memberships are completed with the degree program, though separate applications are necessary.

Program Offered: Degree Completion Pathway in Construction Management and Building Technology
Semesters: Up to 8 semesters (including a field experience semester)
Courses: BLDG 3170, BLDG 3177, BLDG 3178, BLDG 4020, BLDG 4021, BLDG 4050, BLDG 4051, MGMT 4050, MGMT 4052, MGMT 4090, MGMT 4091 (subject to change)
Course Names: Preconstruction Cost Planning, Applications in Building Information Modeling (BIM), Decision Analysis and Critical Thinking, Research Methods, Construction Risk Management, Sustainable Construction, Capstone 2 – Industry Research, Construction Project Procurement 1, Construction Labour Relations and Human Resources, Construction Procurement 2, Leadership and Ethics for Construction Managers
Contact Information: construction_degree@georgebrown.ca or call 416-415-5000, ext. 6297
Learning Outcomes: Effective communication, analysis of past project performance, managing projects in a compliant and sustainable manner, applying management tools and techniques, recognizing and valuing diversity, developing high-functioning teams, analyzing technical problems and developing solutions, managing construction project costs, evaluating potential risks (continuously reviewed and adjusted to meet the needs of the construction industry)
Additional Information: Field experience fee applies for the field experience semester, open to students graduating from George Brown College or a comparable Ontario college with a grade point average of 3.0 or higher in the Building Renovation Technology program (T148)

The home Internet service offers speeds of 25 to 40 Mbps with a ping time of 20–100 ms. Students should consider laptops with the following specifications: operating system - Windows 10 Home 64-bit English, processor - 9th Generation Intel Core i7-9750H, memory (RAM) - 16GB DDR4 2666MHz, disk space - 256GB M.2 PCIe NVMe Solid State Drive and 1TB 5400 rpm 2.5" SATA Hard Drive, display card - NVIDIA GeForce RTX 2060 6GB GDDR6, connectivity - 802.11ac Wi-Fi and Bluetooth, and ports - HDMI 2.0, SuperSpeed USB 3.1 Gen 1 Type-A including one with PowerShare, SD / MicroMedia Card slot, and a Wedge lock slot. The laptop screen size should be minimum 15.6 inches FHD(1920 x 1080) 300nits IPS Anti-Glare LED backlit display with 144Hz refresh rate, and the laptop has one combo headphone / microphone jack. Mac laptops are not recommended due to compatibility issues with many programs.

Domestic students should apply through Ontario Colleges. For more information, contact Angelo DelZotto School of Construction Management at 416-415-5000 ext. 6297 or email construction_degree@georgebrown.ca. Office hours are from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m., room E228. The CCET Industry Liaison Office hosts open houses in the autumn and spring for more information visit Construction and Engineering Open House page. For general information, contact George Brown College Contact Centre at 416-415-2000 (TTY 1-877-515-5559) or long distance 1-800-265-2002. Join on-campus information sessions to meet instructors and staff, ask questions and experience classroom settings by signing up for an information session. Explore related programs through the Hon program webpage.

Students should consider laptops with the following specifications: operating system - Windows 10 Home 64-bit English, processor - 9th Generation Intel Core i7-9750H, memory (RAM) - 16GB DDR4 2666MHz, disk space - 256GB M.2 PCIe NVMe Solid State Drive and 1TB 5400 rpm 2.5" SATA Hard Drive, display card - NVIDIA GeForce RTX 2060 6GB GDDR6, connectivity - 802.11ac Wi-Fi and Bluetooth, and ports - HDMI 2.0, SuperSpeed USB 3.1 Gen 1 Type-A including one with PowerShare, SD / MicroMedia Card slot, and a Wedge lock slot. The laptop screen size should be minimum 15.6 inches FHD(1920 x 1080) 300nits IPS Anti-Glare LED backlit display with 144Hz refresh rate, and the laptop has one combo headphone / microphone jack. Mac laptops are not recommended due to compatibility issues with many programs.

Domestic students should apply through Ontario Colleges. For more information, contact Angelo DelZotto School of Construction Management at 416-415-5000 ext. 6297 or email construction_degree@georgebrown.ca. Office hours are from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m., room E228. The CCET Industry Liaison Office hosts open houses in the autumn and spring for more information visit Construction and Engineering Open House page. For general information, contact George Brown College Contact Centre at 416-415-2000 (TTY 1-877-515-5559) or long distance 1-800-265-2002.
